element_texts.text: Completed

Dear Brother,

    I saw a review of [?] in Dial - May 23 by Untermeyer. What a queasy thing it was - unspeakable unctious and slippery. My mind turned back to your own comments on me in Seven Arts. I remember how honestly you mauled me for my weaknesses and with what fine courage you said good things of me when you thought good things.

    About my going to Kentucky. It seems now almost likely I shall do it. I should know the quiet of a small town for less in a few years. Perhaps I should
Completed

make some money that would give me to follow that two or three years of freedom. You could come there to visit me - wouldn't you?

    Winesburg has gone off to [Law?]. I wonder if the public will really take that book.

    You have not written me of yourself. Are you happy and at work or are you in one empty spot. Tennessee is off to the country for the day. I am pottering in my room. In a few minutes I shall go for a walk.

    Sherwood.
Completed

Dear Brother - The matter of a name bothers me. I want it right. "Mother Night" would be better than "mothering night." There is something choking about the latter.
The Toy Bark - no.
The Cradle Of Man - no.
The [refrain?] from one of my own songs.
"Cradle of Men."
[lines out by SA:] The Lonely Road.
[lined out by SA:] The Mind In The Darkness.
Completed

There must be something peaquant and [evil?] without to much pretension. The Earth gate, Sadling etc. They would all suggest a straining for effect.
Think of "mother night."
Tonight I'll spend an hour or two [grasping?] in the old testament. It will be odd if I do not find what you want there.

    S.A.
Completed

Brother,

    After a night of sleep I find my mind fixed on "Mother Night" as my hunch on the title.

    I had some notion that by going back to the stories of Jacob and Joseph and Saul I should get some word - an encouraging word - coming with sun out of darkness. There is a glow of light that comes sometimes ahead of daylight. In the country it is called "False Dawn." Iy comes - or seems to come and then darkness comes back. That would be a title but it does not, I am afraid, convey what you want to convey.
Completed

I am doing no writing at all - am in fact trying to keep away from pen and paper. Am full of tales wanting to be told but my doctor has told me I am also full of fatigue poison.

    It is confusing to think what I shall do if the doctors tell me - as they practically have - that I will have to give up business or writing. There are the three kids. It's a puzzle.

    S.A.
Completed

about Paul Rosenfelt: At any rate he must not be allowed to believe the army will kill him or drive him insane. If I had his address I would write to him. He must group his way through this thing. He owes it to everybody to come through. I should write him - bravely and [windily?] perhaps - about my own experiences in the army. It might not do any good but I should like to try.

    In regard to your book on America. Would the title
Completed

"Young America" be good. Go softly with the notion of giving so much prominence in the book. Mighty few really think I am worth a damn.

    Yesterday went to a big physician and was gone over well. He says I am O K every way but full of nerve fatigue.

    The country thing would not take me out of business.  I would surely be living in a small quiet place. Would have to do much the same kind of work I do here.
Completed

I figure I would not wear myself out so much. Tennessee would stay here. I would take one of my boys along.

    Think you and Margaret could come out to Michigan the first 2 weeks in July.

    Sherwood.

I like Mother

         Night.
Completed

Old Waldo.

    All east going about with your shining lantern and looking at our west - how be ye. I would like to see you and Margaret. Here I am strutting about New York with my eye cocked up and with my own notions of your damn town farming.

    If you come here you would be telling me what to think - confess it. Stay in the west until I wigwag you to come. Margaret may come anytime.

    Everyone tells me what to
Completed

look at and what to avoid here, everyone but Brooks. I lunched with him in a harden and he never gave me a word of advice/ Was that not charming.

    But I must not bully you always. My love for you is to me so [?] and sure a thing that it delights me to toss it up [with?] the air and catch it as a boy would play with a ball. If you ever [grow?] serious and take my making fun of you as anything more than fooling I'll never forgive you.
Completed

I want to see you at your book as American but I want you also to retain your casual air about it. I have a hunch it is going to be one of the most charming and delightful things you have ever done.

    I have been living in [?]'s apartment at 50 and 5th ave but now have a hole of my own. My goods are going in today. Address me at 427 - W 22nd St. - a nice roomy room in the old Chelsea region with an ancient Irish woman named Rose to take care of me. I looked at a
Completed

hundred places but am sure now I have just what I want.

    Tennessee will be here in September when you et home and we will get up some expiditions to [?] in the sea and do other things.

    - Your letter to me was addressed to John. Didn't have my name on the envelope at all. I was with him at the Lambs when he got it and claimed it at once. "It's mine" I said. He would now be calling you "beloved brother." "Well god damn it, it's addressed to me" he said handing it over.

    You are wrong about the [streets?] book. You have taken it as a piece of writing. Its very stupidity makes it for me, 

    S.A.
Completed

What a nasty letter I wrote you the other day. I started out to tease and didn't quite accomplish my purpose. "If you were here you would be telling me what to think of New York" I said. That was beastly.

    It was unnecessary because if it was true at all it is only true in a meaningles superficial way. I have been so influenced to good by you. I have never been influenced in anything second-rate. You are an egoistical brute but that is your great sensitiveness - I do very deeply love you.

    I was startled to hear that Paul was already in the army. He is at a station near Washington and I am going to Washington to see him next Saturday and Sunday. He begged me to come and offered to pay my R R fare. He can afford
Completed

the expense of course and he does need to be made feel that we who are not in will be carrying him along in our daily thoughts. You can analyze what that means as you will perhaps be in a similar position later. You should be writing Paul, not about your problem and his own but most about the things you are thinking about, your work etc.

    To me dear friend it seems that the great thing is to keep alive the spirit of men at work in the mens delicate and subtile things. The whole other business must as far as possible be treated as a weight-minded elephant would treat the fact of a bee lodged under his ear.

    You will be charmed Waldo with my working place here. The house at 427 West 22 is run by a fine old Irish woman named Rose McCarron
Completed

She arises at dawn and goes to mass. At seven she is back and at 7.30 appears at my door with coffee, toast and fruit.

    Do you realize what it means to me to revise and know an unbroken, uninterrupted morning. Even letters are not opened. Already there creeps back over me the sense of power to handle long unbroken rhythms as when I worked on my long books. If this truly comes back and I can work in the old mood of [unrestricted?] poems, carrying with it also the sense of a positive subtility of understanding gathered from these years of living and of associating with such men as you things may yet be done. I was beginning to be afraid. Now courage comes surging back. As for John [?] - he is a god [awful?] business man. Love to Margie.

    S.A.
